{{Infobox book|| name =Bury Me Standing: The Gypsies and Their Journey | title_orig = | translator = | image = | border = yes | caption = | author =[[Isabel Fonseca]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country =United States of America | language =English | genre = Non-fiction | publisher =[[Random House]] | release_date =1995 | english_release_date = | media_type =Print (hardback and paperback) | pages =322 pp | isbn = 0-679-73743-X | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}'''''Bury Me Standing: The Gypsies and Their Journey''''' is a best-selling non-fiction book on the lives of the [[Romani people]] by the American-Uruguayan writer [[Isabel Fonseca]] published in 1995. Fonseca lived and traveled with the Gypsies of Bulgaria, Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, the former Yugoslavia, Romania and Albania for four years to write the book.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Maslin|first1=Janet|title=A Stranger in the Land of Paradox|journal=The New York Times|date=October 25, 1995|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/09/bsp/bury.html}}</ref> The title "Bury me standing" comes from a proverb which describes the plight of the Gypsies: "Bury me standing. I've been on my knees all my life."
The book is organized in eight chapters and contains black and white photographs and maps.<ref>Fonseca, Isabel "''Bury Me Standing''" Random House. Inc., New York. 1995. Vintage {{ISBN|0-679-73743-X}} ({{ISBN|0-679-40678-6}}). 322 pages including its index. Note: The original hardcover was published by Knopf Inc.</ref>
